\begin_inset Formula $x=p/2^{n}$
\end_inset 

, for 
\begin_inset Formula $n>1$
\end_inset 

, the value 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
t_{w}\left(\frac{p}{2^{n}}\right)=w^{n-1}+\frac{1}{2}\left[t_{w}\left(\frac{p-1}{2^{n}}\right)+t_{w}\left(\frac{p+1}{2^{n}}\right)\right]\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

where we anchor the recurrence with 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{w}(0)=t_{w}(1)=0$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{w}(1/2)=1$
\end_inset 

.
 One extends this curve to all reals by 'linear interpolation' between the
 dyadic values, as 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
t_{w}(x)=\sum_{k=0}^{\infty}w^{k}\tau\left(2^{k}x\right)\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau(x)$
\end_inset 

 is the triangle function:
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\tau(x)=\left\{ \begin{array}{ccc}
2(x-\left\lfloor x\right\rfloor ) & \textrm{\; for \;} & 0\leq x-\left\lfloor x\right\rfloor <1/2\\
2-2(x-\left\lfloor x\right\rfloor ) & \textrm{\; for \;} & 1>x-\left\lfloor x\right\rfloor \geq1/2\end{array}\right.\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 The curve is sometimes presented with 
\begin_inset Formula $2^{-kH}$
\end_inset 

 taking the place of 
\begin_inset Formula $w^{k}$
\end_inset 

 in the series summation, where 
\begin_inset Formula $H=-\log_{2}w$
\end_inset 

 is called the Hurst parameter (need ref).
 The value 
\begin_inset Formula $w=1/4$
\end_inset 

 is special, in that 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{1/4}(x)=4x(1-x)$
\end_inset 

 is a parabola.
 This can perhaps best be seen with the mid-point displacement construction
 of a parabola, which is attributed to Archimedes
\begin_inset LatexCommand \cite{Man88}

\end_inset 

.
 A prototypical Takagi-Landsberg curve is shown in figure 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{cap:The-Takagi-Landsberg-Curve}

\end_inset 


\layout Standard

In a certain technical sense, the curve is not differentiable at any dyadic
 value 
\begin_inset Formula $x=p/2^{n}$
\end_inset 

, as such values correspond to the tip of the triangle wave, where the derivativ
e is ill-defined.
 However, one can still perform derivative-like manipulations with the curve,
 which will be explored in greater detail below.
 For example, one may choose to define the derivative 
\begin_inset Formula $dt_{w}/dx$
\end_inset 

 by passing the 
\begin_inset Formula $d/dx$
\end_inset 

 past the summation, to act on the triangle-wave, replacing it with a square
 wave.
 The result is a curve that is discontinuous everywhere, but does have a
 number of derivative-like properties.
\layout Standard

One can generalize this curve in a variety of ways, for example, by replacing
 the tent 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau(x)$
\end_inset 

 with any 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset 

 on the unit interval.
 To get a continuous Takagi curve, one must have 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset 

 continuous and have 
\begin_inset Formula $f(0)=f(1)$
\end_inset 

.
 Discontinuous functions 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset 

 yield curves that are discontinuous everywhere: for example, the square
 wave 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma(x)=d\tau/dx=1-2\left\lfloor 2x\right\rfloor $
\end_inset 

 gives the self-similar shape shown in the figures
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{cap:Cantor-Polynomial}

\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{cap:cantor-sawtooth}

\end_inset 

 below.
 
\layout Standard

Of the many possible different choices for 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset 

, the triangle wave is special in that it stays self-similar through iteration;
 that is, 
\begin_inset Formula $(\tau\diamond\tau)(x)\equiv\tau^{2}(x)=\tau(2x)$
\end_inset 

 and generally, iterating on it 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset 

 times gives 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau^{k}(x)=\tau(2^{k-1}x)$
\end_inset 

.
 Thus, one may write 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
t_{w}(x)=\sum_{k=0}^{\infty}w^{k}\tau^{k+1}(x)\label{eq:tee-w}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 
