\layout Subsection

Symmetries of the Takagi Curve
\layout Standard

This section demonstrates that the Takagi curve transforms as a three-dimensiona
l representation of the tree-walking monoid.
 This provides an example where the action of the monoid can be precisely
 and completely specified.
 
\layout Standard

The interval contraction generator 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset 

 acts on the Takagi map as
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\left[gt_{w}\right](x)=\left(t_{w}\circ g_{D}\right)(x)=t_{w}\left(\frac{x}{2}\right)=x+wt_{w}(x)\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 Iterating on this generator gives 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\left[g^{n}t_{w}\right](x)=t_{w}\left(\frac{x}{2^{n}}\right)=\frac{x}{2^{n-1}}\left(\frac{1-2^{n}w^{n}}{1-2w}\right)+w^{n}t_{w}(x)\label{eq: power of two value}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 The action of 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset 

 is considerably more trivial: 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\left[rt_{w}\right](x)=\left(t_{w}\circ r_{D}\right)(x)=t_{w}\left(1-x\right)=t_{w}(x)\]

\end_inset 

 since the Takagi curve is left-right symmetric.
 Thus, it is easily seen that the actions of 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset 

 on a general expression 
\begin_inset Formula $a+bx+ct_{w}(x)$
\end_inset 

 always returns another expression of the same type; and that the actions
 are both linear and also closed.
 That is, a general expression 
\begin_inset Formula $a+bx+ct_{w}(x)$
\end_inset 

 can be interpreted as a vector in a three-dimensional vector space, and
 the action 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset 

 have representation as operators on that space.
 We have that the Takagi Curve transforms under a three-dimensional representati
on of the monoid.
 
\layout Standard

This may be made explicit as follows.
 Write a general element of the vector space as the dot-product of a row
 of real numbers times a column of basis vectors 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
a+bx+ct_{w}(x)=\left(\begin{array}{ccc}
a & \; b & \; c\end{array}\right)\left(\begin{array}{c}
1\\
x\\
t_{w}(x)\end{array}\right)\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset 

 have the representations 
\layout Standard


\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
g_{3}=\left(\begin{array}{ccc}
1\; & 0\; & 0\\
0 & \frac{1}{2} & 0\\
0 & 1 & w\end{array}\right)\;\textrm{ and \;}r_{3}=\left(\begin{array}{ccc}
1\; & 0\; & 0\\
1 & -1\; & 0\\
0 & 0 & 1\end{array}\right)\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 where the subscript 3 is used to denote that this is a 3-D representation.
 Under the action of this representation, 3-vectors transform as, for example,
 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\left[gt_{w}\right](x)=\left(\begin{array}{ccc}
0 & \;0 & \;1\end{array}\right)\left(\begin{array}{ccc}
1\; & 0\; & 0\\
0 & \frac{1}{2} & 0\\
0 & 1 & w\end{array}\right)\left(\begin{array}{c}
1\\
x\\
t_{w}(x)\end{array}\right)\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 This should be compared to the transformation properties of dyadic numbers.
 By a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset 

dyadic number
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset 

, we mean a real number represented as a string of binary digits
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
x=\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}b_{n}2^{-n}\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 with the binary digits 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{n}$
\end_inset 

 being either 0 or 1.
 By replacing the number 2 with a different number, it is easily seen that
 the dyadic representation forms a Cantor Set (discussed in greater detail
 below), and that it's self-similarity properties are also given by the
 same semigroup/monoid that describes the Takagi curve.
 However, the representation of the transformation properties is a two-dimension
al representation.
 That is, the dyadic representation that acted on dyadic numbers arranged
 in a doublet 
\begin_inset Formula $(1,x)$
\end_inset 

 as 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
g_{D}=\left(\begin{array}{cc}
1 & 0\\
0 & \frac{1}{2}\end{array}\right)\;\textrm{ and }\; r_{D}=\left(\begin{array}{cc}
1 & 0\\
1 & -1\end{array}\right)\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 Alternately, one may write 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{D}(x)=x/2$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{D}(x)=1-x$
\end_inset 

 when acting on real numbers.
 The 3D representation is then seen to be a an extension of the 2D vector
 space.
 The Takagi Curve commutes with the generators as 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[g_{3}t_{w}\right]\left(x\right)=\left(t_{w}\circ g_{D}\right)\left(x\right)$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[r_{3}t_{w}\right](x)=\left(t_{w}\circ r_{D}\right)\left(x\right)$
\end_inset 

 where the left hand side is taken as an operator equation, and the right
 hand side as function composition.
\layout Standard

This can be further belabored by examining the formulas for a general contractin
g group element 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma=g^{a_{1}}rg^{a_{2}}rg^{a_{3}}r...rg^{a_{N}}\in PSL(2,\mathbb{Z})$
\end_inset 

.
 By 'contracting' we mean that we want to take all 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{k}>0$
\end_inset 

.
 The contracting elements form the monoid, and we explicitly want to avoid
 considering the inverses of these group elements.
 Trying to incorporate the inverses significantly complicates the analysis,
 and a full inclusion of all inverses cannot be satisfactorily done.
 
\layout Standard

We have that 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset 

 acts on the real number 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset 

 with the dyadic representation: that is, 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\gamma:x=\gamma_{D}(x)=\frac{1}{2^{a_{1}}}-\frac{1}{2^{a_{1}+a_{2}}}+\frac{1}{2^{a_{1}+a_{2}+a_{3}}}-...+(-)^{N+1}\frac{x}{2^{a_{1}+a_{2}+a_{3}+...+a_{N}}}\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 which can be quickly computed by multiplying together the representation
 matrices 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{D}$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{D}$
\end_inset 

.
 By contrast, on the Takagi curve, 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset 

 acts as 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{3}$
\end_inset 

, thus: 
\layout Standard


\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\left[\gamma_{3}t_{w}\right](x)=t_{w}(\gamma_{D}(x))=\left(\begin{array}{ccc}
0 & \;0 & \;1\end{array}\right)g_{3}^{a_{1}}r_{3}g_{3}^{a_{2}}r_{3}g_{3}^{a_{3}}r_{3}...r_{3}g_{3}^{a_{N}}\left(\begin{array}{c}
1\\
x\\
t_{w}(x)\end{array}\right)\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 which demonstrates the self-symmetry of the curve for arbitrary (contracting)
 element 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma\in PSL(2,\mathbb{Z})$
\end_inset 

.
 That is, we have demonstrated an isomorphism between the set of contracting
 elements 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma\in PSL(2,\mathbb{Z})$
\end_inset 

 and a subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $GL(3,\mathbb{R})$
\end_inset 

 generated by 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{3}$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{3}$
\end_inset 

.
 Note that this isomorphism is only between subsets, and not subgroups:
 the monoid does not contain its inverses.
\layout Standard

Equivalently, this set of contracting elements is isomorphic to the set
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Q}\times\mathbb{N}\times\mathbb{Z}_{2}$
\end_inset 

: pick any 
\begin_inset Formula $p/q\in\mathbb{Q}$
\end_inset 

 and set 
\begin_inset Formula $p/q=\gamma_{D}(0)$
\end_inset 

 which fixes the values of 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{1},...,a_{N-1}$
\end_inset 

.
 Then pick a positive integer 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{N}\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset 

 which fixes 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{D}(1)$
\end_inset 

.
 This fixes the two endpoints of the interval that contains the self-similar
 portion of the Takagi curve.
 Then pick from 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}_{2}$
\end_inset 

 to decide if the mapping should invert the interval or not.
 Thus it is seen just how fine-grained, and also how constrained, the notion
 of self-similarity is.
 One may pick an interval one of whose endpoints may start on 
\emph on 
any
\emph default 
 rational, but once one endpoint has been specified, one only has a limited
 (albeit countably infinite) choice for the other endpoint.
 
\layout Description

Caution: The above has only demonstrated an isomorphism for the contracting
 (and their inverses, the expanding) group elements.
 General group elements also map intervals to intervals, but these may or
 may not be intersecting.
 When a pair of intervals do intersect, then there is a 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{D}(x)$
\end_inset 

 that is valid and defined on the interval, and thus the Takagi curve, restricte
d to that interval, demonstrates the desired isomorphism.
 When a pair of intervals do not intersect, then we do not have this demonstrati
on, and so the above arguments fail.
 A rigorous treatment for general group elements seems to require a discussion
 of the topology of the modular group, of how to extend the mappings to
 the remaining group elements from those that can be easily handled.
 It is not clear if a consistent extension is possible, nor is it clear
 how to describe the obstruction if its not.
 This is beyond the level of the current presentation.
\layout Description

