\layout Subsection

The Cantor Polynomials 
\layout Standard

The action of a group element 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset 

 on the Takagi curve can be written as 
\layout Standard


\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
t_{w}(\gamma_{D}(x))=p_{\gamma}(w)+x\, q_{\gamma}(w)+w^{M_{\gamma}}t_{w}(x)\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 for some polynomials 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{\gamma}$
\end_inset 

, 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{\gamma}$
\end_inset 

 and positive integer 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{\gamma}$
\end_inset 

 where we use the subscript 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset 

 to denote that they depend on the particular 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset 

 chosen.
 A brief bit of scratching shows what the 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{\gamma}$
\end_inset 

 polynomial is; but 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{\gamma}$
\end_inset 

 is harder.
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma=g^{a_{1}}rg^{a_{2}}rg^{a_{3}}r...rg^{a_{N}}$
\end_inset 

 as before, one has 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{\gamma}=a_{1}+...+a_{N}$
\end_inset 

.
 Writing out the binary expansion for 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{D}(1)$
\end_inset 

 in terms of binary digits 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{k}\in\left\{ 0,1\right\} $
\end_inset 

, one has 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{eqnarray}
\gamma_{D}(1) & = & \sum_{k=1}^{\infty}\frac{b_{k}}{2^{k}}\nonumber \\
\, & = & \begin{array}{ccccc}
0. & \underbrace{000...000} & \underbrace{111...111} & \underbrace{000...000} & ...\\
\, & a_{1} & a_{2} & a_{3} & \,\end{array}\label{eq:}\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset 

 where, as usual, one takes the expansion such that the final binary digits
 repeat forever, without upsetting the count 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{N}$
\end_inset 

 of the previous digits; that is, 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
b_{k}=\left\{ \begin{array}{ccc}
1 & \;\textrm{ for N odd, }\; & \forall k>M\\
0 & \;\textrm{ for N even, }\; & \forall k>M\end{array}\right.\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 The polynomial 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{\gamma}$
\end_inset 

 can then be expressed directly in terms of this binary expansion.
 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
q_{\gamma}(w)=\frac{(-)^{N}}{2^{M-1}}\sum_{k=1}^{M}(2b_{k}-1)\;(2w)^{k-1}\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{\gamma}$
\end_inset 

 is more-or-less equal (up to a factor and a term of 
\begin_inset Formula $1/(1-2w)$
\end_inset 

) to the derivative
\begin_inset Formula \[
\left.\frac{dt_{w}(x)}{dx}\right|_{x=\gamma_{D}(1)}\]

\end_inset 

 We say 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset 

more or less
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset 

 because some care has to be taken to define which bit expansion defines
 the derivative.
 In a certain sense, 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{\gamma}$
\end_inset 

 is the dis-ambiguated derivative.
 This is left as an exercise.
 
\layout Standard

The 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{\gamma}$
\end_inset 

 polynomial seems to result from some more complex folding that is hard
 to discern by studying the matrix elements under matrix multiplication.
 However, determining its value for any given 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset 

 is straightforward enough: we merely need to set 
\begin_inset Formula $x=0$
\end_inset 

 to find 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{\gamma}(w)=t_{w}(\gamma_{D}(0))$
\end_inset 

.
